On Thu, Sep 11, 2003 at 02:25:57PM -0400, Ken MacLeod wrote:
&gt; HttpMethodsSupport[1] is copied from the Atom Wiki CarrotVsOrange
&gt; page[2], summarizing the support of PUT and DELETE methods in various
&gt; server and client toolkits.
&gt; 
&gt; While very promising for REST overall, the smattering of toolkits that
&gt; only support GET/POST may be cause for Pie/Echo/Atom to also support a
&gt; fallback technique.

There&#39;s a middle ground here.  It&#39;s not perfectly RESTful, but is more
so than the everything-with-POST approach.  And what&#39;s making it
unRESTful is HTTP&#39;s lack of mandatory extensions (at least I think
that&#39;s the only thing).

A PUT would look like this;

POST /moby HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/not-echo+xml
Action: http://some-pie-uri.example.org/intent/put

&lt;?xml version=&#39;1.0&#39;?&gt;
&lt;entry&gt;
 &lt;title&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/title&gt;
 &lt;author&gt;&lt;name&gt;Herman Melville&lt;/name&gt;&lt;/author&gt;
 &lt;created&gt;1851-10-18T02:00:00Z&lt;/created&gt;
 &lt;content type=&#39;text/plain&#39;&gt;Call me Ishmael.&lt;/content&gt;
 &lt;/entry&gt;

and a &quot;DELETE /moby&quot; would look like this;

POST /moby HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/not-echo+xml
Action: http://some-pie-uri.example.org/intent/delete
[zero length body]

&quot;Action&quot; serves to identify the &quot;extended intent&quot; of the POST
submission.  It&#39;s the non-SOAP version of SOAPAction.

As mentioned, all that&#39;s missing for this to be fully RESTful, I
believe, is mandatory extensions.  So a more RESTful PUT-via-POST
example, using RFC 2774 which adds mandatory extensions to HTTP,
would be (though I&#39;m *not* proposing this);

M-POST /moby HTTP/1.1
Content-Type: application/not-echo+xml
Man: &quot;http://some-pie-uri.example.org/pie-ns/&quot;; ns=1
1-Action: http://some-pie-uri.example.org/intent/put

&lt;?xml version=&#39;1.0&#39;?&gt;
&lt;entry&gt;
 &lt;title&gt;Chapter 1&lt;/title&gt;
 &lt;author&gt;&lt;name&gt;Herman Melville&lt;/name&gt;&lt;/author&gt;
 &lt;created&gt;1851-10-18T02:00:00Z&lt;/created&gt;
 &lt;content type=&#39;text/plain&#39;&gt;Call me Ishmael.&lt;/content&gt;
 &lt;/entry&gt;

I&#39;d still like to be able to use PUT and DELETE though.  But doing
this in addition would seem to address the concerns of the folks who
are concerned about the lack of widespread support for PUT and
DELETE.

Mark.
